<div id="review_14001910" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/14001910" />
    <a title="Leah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/581687-leah"><img alt="Leah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1193754530p2/581687.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/14001910?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leah" href="/user/show/581687-leah">Leah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone who likes war movies because they wish they were in them</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer14001910" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8964746533180847234">Outstanding book. The author (a former war reporter) discusses the addictive nature of war, both for soldiers and the public. &quot;War&quot; becomes an idealized fiction that we rally around--that &quot;gives us meaning,&quot; gives us a purpose, gives us a way to join together as a nation, but that the actual reality of what a war is and what it entails is beyond any experience that one can truly describe. War is beyond hell. A true experience of war is something that can never be captured in a movie, book, or ne</span>
  <span id="freeText8964746533180847234" style="display:none">Outstanding book. The author (a former war reporter) discusses the addictive nature of war, both for soldiers and the public. "War" becomes an idealized fiction that we rally around--that "gives us meaning," gives us a purpose, gives us a way to join together as a nation, but that the actual reality of what a war is and what it entails is beyond any experience that one can truly describe. War is beyond hell. A true experience of war is something that can never be captured in a movie, book, or news report. The true terrible scale of what is happening is something that can only be experienced and damages those who truly experience it in such a way that they cannot really talk about it (this is the common story of the soldiers who've seen the least "action" are the ones who talk the most, while those who really saw the war first-hand keep quite silent). He describes participating in the war, your life on the possible fringe of life and death, as a rush or a high that ultimately becomes a dangerous addiction which he has now removed himself from after a lifetime of witnessing war up-close and first-hand. <br /><br />The writing is dry and straightforward, but the message is incredibly important, especially for those who are caught up in the fictional movie/video-game war land. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8964746533180847234" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


